Privileges — what each one actually buys the grantee. This is a recognition list; the exam expects you to know these on sight, so let's walk the important ones.

Use-catalog lets you see the schemas inside a catalog. Use-schema lets you see the objects inside a schema. Select lets you read rows from a table, view, or materialized view. Modify is the write privilege — it covers insert, update, delete, and merge, plus alter for schema changes. Create, and its finer-grained cousins create-table and create-schema, let you make new objects inside a catalog or schema. Execute lets you call a function. Read-volume and write-volume let you read or write files in a volume. Browse lets you see an object's metadata — its name and comments — without seeing the data. Apply-tag lets you tag an object for governance, which matters for A-B-A-C later. And all-privileges grants every privilege at that level — use it sparingly.

Now, a concept that sits alongside privileges but is separate from them: ownership. The owner of an object can do anything to it, including changing its grants. There is exactly one owner per object, and you transfer ownership with alter-owner-to a group. That's a different thing from a privilege — an owner doesn't need to be granted select; they simply have full control.

Finally, two distinctions the exam specifically tests. First, select versus modify — select is read, modify is the single write privilege covering insert, update, delete, and merge. Second, browse versus select — browse lets you see that an object exists and view its metadata, while select lets you actually read its rows. And a best-practice note: prefer owning objects with groups, not individuals, so that ownership survives when a person leaves the team.
